title: Remove outdated gulp closure compiler wrapper and use original one
body:
Also added replace function to use with gulp pipe. 

As [gulp-closure-compiler](https://github.com/steida/gulp-closure-compiler) is pretty old and no longer updated I've removed it from our dependencies and used gulp plugin that comes directly with `google-closure-compiler`. I have also adapted config to work with newest version of closure compiler.

There was also an issue that `gulp-closure-compiler` did not work correctly with gulp pipes (found in #1663). All the changes made to files before compilation were removed.

Everything now works as intended.

title: TPR instances list
body:
Added TPR instances list to its details view:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2823399/23657739/f5283b62-033f-11e7-9e1c-442ef6cc8c4f.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2823399/23657751/001e9dfe-0340-11e7-9839-7d768e9ae630.png)

Things to consider for the future:

- [ ] If there are >3 TPRs perhaps we should display only 3 of them **in the menu** and in the next line put a link to list of all of them (something like `... and X more`)

Related to #1504.

title: Fix frontend tests
body:
Fixes frontend tests that are failing after updating angular to 1.6. Travis is green because we haven't removed cached dependencies.

Default [$locationProvider](https://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng/provider/$locationProvider) prefix has changed to `!` now and unhandled promise rejections cause errors so they have to be handled by us now.

title: Fix in cluster config
body:
There was an issue during 1.6 release that prevented users from creating dashboard using in-cluster config. Only apiserver-host parameter allowed to use dashboard. It is related to client-go migration.

### Breaking change
Client-go requires ServiceAccounts to be enabled for in-cluster configuration. We have to add notes to our docs and release notes that starting from this version cluster has to have SA enabled and properly configured.

@kubernetes/dashboard-maintainers

title: Add basic html/go formatting and common gulp format script
body:
Added go/html formatting. HTML formatter will preserve bigger part of the code. It will only split and keep all tag attributes aligned in new lines, keep line indentation set to 2, and try to preserve max line length which is now 120. Additionally it will add new lines on end of each file so we don't have to worry about that anymore.

I've also added task for go formatting (`gulp format-go`) and exposed one common `gulp format` task to format JS, HTML and Go code at once.

title: Add support for sorting and fix minor issues
body:
It required some major changes in frontend. Currently sorting is supported for 3 types of columns: name, status and age. 

In order to add support for sorting to the existing list open the cardlist.html template and add i.e.: `sortable="true"` and `sord-id=$root.SortableProperties.NAME` to the `kd-resource-card-header-column` representing name column. It will enable sorting for this column and use corresponding backend method for sorting.

## Important changes
 - Created `DataSelectService` instead of `PaginationService` that handles all kinds of data selection, including: sorting, filtering, paging. Currently sorting and paging is implemented.
 - Moved `list`, `list-resource` and `data-select-id` dependency from `kd-resource-card-list-pagination` to `kd-resource-card-list`. It will be shared with child components thanks to parent - child relationship between components.
 - Moved data select ids to corresponding component controller `getSelectId` method. In case if it's empty, data select logic will not be applied to the list.
 - By default all resources will be sorted by age in the ascending order. From youngest to oldest one.
 - In order to share supported SortableProperties I have added run config to DataSelect module and injected them into the rootScope that is by default available in all templates by executing `$root.SortableProperties.NAME`. I'm not sure if there is a better way to do that. They are const values so there should be no risk with exposing them in root scope.

## Additional changes
 - Add missing graph cards to cluster view.
 - Update closure compiler externs to version 1.6
 - Enable console log usage in karma tests
 - Add missing externs to `backendapi.js`
 - Update `foreground-3` css variable to match material design spec

UI:

Default sorting by age

title: Allow default setttings override for serve and serve:prod
body:
Currently when using `serve` or `serve:prod` dashboard could only connect to local cluster. In order to change that we've had to change build files. I have changed that to first check environment variables, then use predefined ones.

This allows to easily configure build pipeline to use external cluster for `serve` and `serve:prod`, i.e. I'm using kubeconfig env variable to connect to minikube cluster that by default is secured and does not expose insecure api server port.

Environment variables:
 - `KUBE_DASHBOARD_APISERVER_HOST` - do `export KUBE_DASHBOARD_APISERVER_HOST=<HOST>` to override default api server url
 - `KUBE_DASHBOARD_KUBECONFIG` - do `export KUBE_DASHBOARD_KUBECONFIG=<PATH>` to use kubeconfig file instead of api server host param. Kubeconfig env variable has higher priority than apiserver host.

~I will also adjust the documentation.~ Done.

title: Scaling for a Deployment, ReplicaSet, Replication Controller, or Job.
body:
Fixes https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/1560

Scale or set a new size for a Deployment, ReplicaSet, Replication Controller. In the case of a job it will adjust the parallelism for the said job.

title: Fixes build error...
body: Build seems to failing due to some incorrect paths defined for google closure compiler...

title: Make timestamp toggable
body:
In Dashboard Logs-View we currently show the timestamp, always. In kubectl the timestamp is not shown by default, but can be enabled (--timestamp=true)

The timestamp is required in the backend for pagination. I refactored the code to be able to strip off the timestamp. Seems to work. Maybe I should do some more refactoring for beautification, because there a several similar objects. I will check. 

The toggle button in the UI is also missing

Will fix: https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/1546

title: Switch to Material Design Icons library
body:

Old icon set: https://material.io/icons/
New icon set: https://materialdesignicons.com/

**If we will agree on this change I will refactor other icons across the Dashboard. Currently did it only in few places.**

Moreover, while I was doing it I refactored a bit status code on resource cards. We can use `ng-switch` there to make it easier to maintain.

Fixes #1460.

title: Use a github owned domain for install documentation
body:
`whois rawgit.com` uses `contactprivacy.email` which means there is no
visible accountability for that domain.

`ping rawgit.com` shows it terminates in CloudFlare, which means there
is TLS decapsulation outside of the github.com trust domain. This makes
it not possible to verify end-to-end encryption to github.com content.

Running `kubectl apply -f <url>` assumes a trusted source and no
tampering.

`rawgit.com` leaves the trust of github.com and opens the possibility
for man-in-the-middle attacks.

Github can serve raw content from a domain under their control at
`raw.githubusercontent.com`. By using this domain, whois shows the
owner, and provides end-to-end encryption to github.com content.

title: Add sorting support to remaining list resources
body:
## Additional changes
 - Add age column to all resources as by default we are sorting by age
 - Update backend documentation
 - `gofmt` backend
 - Clean up horizontal pod autoscalers frontend code to correctly support sorting
 - Disable sorting in case list resource is not provided instead of throwing an error

Last change is done due to i.e. deployment's new replica sets not having it's own endpoint for updates. As there is always only one new replica set and we are using list to display it I am not sure if having separate endpoint is good. We don't need sorting nor paging on such lists so we can disable it instead of throwing an error.

Closes #1677.

title: fix server crashed when upload yaml in 1.6
body:
## how to present problem
1. start container:
`docker run --rm -ti -p 9090:9090 gcr.io/google_containers/kubernetes-dashboard-amd64:v1.6.0 --apiserver-host=http://192.168.0.10:8080 `

2. click "Create" and upload a yaml.

3. the server crashed, and error like below:
```
Using apiserver-host location: http://localhost:8080
Creating API server client for http://localhost:8080
Error while initializing connection to Kubernetes apiserver. This most likely means that the cluster is misconfigured (e.g., it has invalid apiserver certificates or service accounts configuration) or the
 --apiserver-host param points to a server that does not exist. Reason: Get http://localhost:8080/version: dial tcp [::1]:8080: getsockopt: connection refused
```

## what I do
according to https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/pull/1739 , I just modify the deploy part.

## how to check
`gulp serve` to check first, and then `gulp docker-image:release:cross` build image and run container to check again.

Signed-off-by: wefine <wang.xiaoren@zte.com.cn>

If someone is able to, it would be even more awesome if you could have a drop down selector for each list view and change between some default values like 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 100 etc.

title: Fix deploy from file not respecting namespaces and introduce localizer for backend error messages
body:
This change fixes #1374 and #974.

## Changes
 - Introduced error localization mechanism
 - Fixed #1374

## TODO
 - [x] Clean up the code

## Error localizer
I have introduced a mechanism to localize messages coming from backend. Basically it is based on 2 maps that have to be synchronized on backend and frontend side.

`backend[partial -> code] -> frontend[code -> msg]`

Backend map structure:
 - key: unique partial string used to differentate message coming from api server. Some errors have their own api and are exposed as const objects so we can also use them.
 - value: unique error code string that can be recognized by frontend and used for localization

Frontend map structure:
 - key: basically it is backend's map value
 - value: message localized with `goog.getMsg`.

Additionally I have created `LocalizerService` that will take error string and localize it or return original string if it is not recognized.

## Main fix description
Basically we have 5 cases to consider (i'm assuming that namespace is always correct and exists):

1. Namespace is set in both file and dashboard and
   1. they are equal - **OK**
   1. they are different - **NOK** error is thrown that there is namespace mismatch between dashboard and yaml file.
1. Namespace is set in file and all namespaces are set in dashboard - **OK**
1. Namespace is set in dashboard but not set in file - **OK**
1. No namespace in both file and dashboard (all namespaces) - **NOK** error is thrown that namespace is not selected in both file and in dashboard

### UI

Case 1.2
![zrzut ekranu z 2017-04-28 15-37-53](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2285385/25531058/c4671298-2c28-11e7-8cb6-d9e1741065ce.png)

title: Pod attach/exec proto
body:
**Prototype** -- please comment extensively. This is building on code/ideas/comments from #1455 and #1345, so some of the problems/suggestions mentioned there are addressed.

Task list:
- [x] Builds prod
- [x] You can actually execute a shell and get a terminal in the containers
- [x] Support trying different shells (tries `bash` than `sh` for now)
- [x] Using hterm. So copy-paste, colors, mouse, etc.
- [x] Resizing
- [x] Moon buggy!!
- [x] Message on disconnect
- [x] SockJS transport (kubectl proxy does not support websockets (kubernetes/kubernetes#32026) which is a major use case. So if websockets do not work it falls back on different kinds of http streaming. It is jerkier and much less efficient than websockets but at least it works.)
- [ ] Ability to attach as in kubectl attach
- [x] Come up with a better name than "Attach" for the shell exec link
- [x] Make code look not horrible. For example, find better names for all the `*attach*` functions and structures. Dependencies for gorilla/websocket should be removed.
- [ ] Implement locking for session map (while the current code is _bad_, actually triggering the problem is unlikely)
- [ ] Add links leading to exec view (something like logs button)
- [ ] Serve `SockJSURL` from dashboard
- [ ] utf-8 _input_ (needs hterm needs configuration)
- [ ] Add some tests
- [ ] Some solution to respawn if the user exits the shell (?)
- [ ] Some padding on the left (?)

I have been running it like this:
`DOCKER_RUN_OPTS="-v $HOME/.kube/config:/kubeconfig.yaml:ro -e KUBE_DASHBOARD_KUBECONFIG=/kubeconfig.yaml" build/run-gulp-in-docker.sh serve
`

![moon-buggy](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1122543/25977317/afb82866-36b2-11e7-8a14-811543485067.png)

title: Refactor api client creation
body:
Fixes #1998 

I have prepared client manager that is responsible for creating client on every request, generating csrfKey, handling auth, etc.

There are many files changed as I've had to move some general types to single directory. They are now under `api/types.go`. We could think of moving all our api structures that we have in `backendapi.js` there.

### Key files changed/moved
`apihandler.go` - moved code to other files
`apiserverclient.go` - removed and some code moved to `client/manager.go`
`heapsterclient.go` moved to `integration/metric/heapster/client.go` as that's where I keep on my branch where I'm working on integrations page.
`filter.go` - contains filter methods that were in `apihandler.go` before
`verber.go` moved to `client/verber.go` as it is also a client and is created by `ClientManager`

Changes in other files are renaming old packages to new ones. I have tested external config, in-cluster config and auth header and it works.

TODO
 - [x] Add documentation
 - [x] Add some tests

title: Load logs with memory limits
body:
Fixes https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/1834

Kubernetes stores logs in files and rotates them once a day if they become too large. Up to now Dashboard loads the full log file from server and returns a small portion to the browser.

I changed the behavior to return only a number of pages in the beginning and end. In other words the first 50 pages and the last 50 pages are loaded.

title: Introduce integration framework backend
body:
There are still lots of things to be done. I have decided to take care of config storage and sync in next PRs as this will be already a big change. Any comments are appreciated.

## Major changes
 - Added `IntegrationManager` that will be responsible for providing state of integration app (installed, connected, enabled, etc.) and listing all integrations. 
- Added `MetricManager` as a dependency of `IntegrationManager`. It represents group of metric integrations like heapster, prometheus, etc. It will be responsible for controlling status of all metric integrations and providing active metric client.
- Added `MetricClient` interface as a layer of abstraction between resources and metric api. All metric integrations will have to implement that interface.
- Removed all hard dependencies on heapster from our sources and replaced them with `MetricClient`.

Rules for introducing new integration would be:
1. Implement `Integration` interface to make sure that every integration app has unique ID and can do a health check to make sure if we can enable it.
1. Introduce new group-like interface that will be responsible for handling new integration. I'm thinking about adding interface similar to `Integration` that will make sure that every 'group' can handle integrations, i.e. install/uninstall or enable/disable them.

Later on they should support storage thus implement necessary methods that will make sure that state of integrations is persisted and up to date.

### TODO
 - [x] Agree on the integration framework API
 - [x] Clean up code
 - [x] Finish heapster migration (~graphs are working, sparklines not~)
 - [x] Add documentation
 - [x] Add tests

body:
Letâ€™s get started with automated dependency management for dashboard :muscle:



This pull request **updates all your dependencies to their latest version**. Having them all up to date really is the best starting point. I will look out for further dependency updates and make sure to handle them in isolation and in real-time, **as soon as you merge this pull request**.

**I wonâ€™t start sending you further updates, unless you have merged this very pull request**.



---
<details>
<summary>ðŸ’¥ This branch failed. How to proceed</summary>

I suggest you find out what dependency update is causing the problem. Adapt your code so things are working nicely together again. [next-update](https://www.npmjs.com/package/next-update) is a really handy tool to help you with this.

Push the changes to this branch and merge it.
</details>
<details>
<summary>ðŸ· How to check the status of this repository</summary>

There is a badge added to your README, indicating the status of this repository.

This is how your badge looks like :point_right:  ![Greenkeeper badge](https://badges.greenkeeper.io/kubernetes/dashboard.svg)
</details>
<details>
<summary>ðŸ™ˆ How to ignore certain dependencies</summary>

In case you can not, or do not want to update a certain dependency right now, you can of course just [change the `package.json` file back to your liking](https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/edit/greenkeeper/initial/package.json).

Add a `greenkeeper.ignore` field to your `package.json`, containing a list of dependencies you donâ€™t want to update right now.

```js
// package.json
{
  â€¦
  "greenkeeper": {
    "ignore": [
      "package-names",
      "you-want-me-to-ignore"
    ]
  }
}
```
</details>
<details>
<summary>ðŸ‘©â€ðŸ’» How to update this pull request</summary>

```bash
  # change into your repositoryâ€™s directory
  git fetch
  git checkout greenkeeper/initial
  npm install-test
  # adapt your code, so itâ€™s working again
  git commit -m 'chore: adapt code to updated dependencies'
  git push origin greenkeeper/initial
```
</details>
<details>
<summary>âœ¨ How the updates will look like</summary>

As soon as you merge this pull request **Iâ€™ll create a branch for every dependency update**, with the new version applied. The branch creation should trigger your testing services to check the new version. Using the results of these tests Iâ€™ll try to open meaningful and helpful pull requests and issues, so your dependencies remain working and up-to-date.

```diff
-  "underscore": "^1.6.0"
+  "underscore": "^1.7.0"
```

In the above example you can see an in-range update. `1.7.0` is included in the old `^1.6.0` range, because of the [caret `^` character ](https://docs.npmjs.com/misc/semver#ranges).
When the test services report success Iâ€™ll delete the branch again, because no action needs to be taken â€“ everything is fine.
When there is a failure however, Iâ€™ll create an issue so you know about the problem immediately.

This way every single version update of your dependencies will either continue to work with your project, or youâ€™ll get to know of potential problems immediately.

```diff
-  "lodash": "^3.0.0"
+  "lodash": "^4.0.0"
```

In this example the new version `4.0.0` is not included in the old `^3.0.0` range.
For version updates like these â€“ letâ€™s call them â€œout of rangeâ€ updates â€“ youâ€™ll receive a pull request.

Now **you no longer need to check for exciting new versions by hand** â€“ Iâ€™ll just let you know automatically.
And the pull request will not only serve as a reminder to update. In case it passes your decent test suite thatâ€™s a strong reason to merge right away :shipit:
</details>

<summary>ðŸ’â€â™‚ï¸ Not sure how things are going to work exactly?</summary>

title: [WIP] Update documentation for single/multi tenant configurations
body:
Closes #2045. Related to discussion started in #574.

First we have to state what we will support. What I think we should do is:

1. Provide good documentation for latest supported kubernetes release (currently 1.6).
1. Provide option to deploy on older clusters but leave advanced configuration up to the users. Only basic yaml without RBAC configuration.
1. Split deployment into 2 parts: dashboard, rbac configuration
1. Document details about single/multi tenant approach that our proposed configuration supports.
1. For multi-tenant setup describe how to authorize users using authorization header and tokens but without specific examples as we don't have enough people to maintain them well.
1. Simplify head releases and support only latest kubernetes versions with full access to the cluster (by providing yaml file). Of course we will add information about that to warn potential users.
1. Remove other arch yaml files and just document what architectures we support with example that in order to deploy for different arch user can use this command `curl -sSL <dashboard_url> | sed "s/amd64/arm64/g" | kubectl create -f -`
1. State that `kubectl proxy` is not the right way to authorize users for multi-tenant configurations.

I have updated documentation a bit and if we agree on required changes I will update yamls and remaining docs.

Calling everyone involved in discussion. 

@bryk @cheld @rf232 @liggitt @maciaszczykm

title: Enhance error handling/authorization
body:
### Changes

- Every resource list structure now have `list of non-critical errors, that occurred during resource retrieval`. It allows to silence these errors and avoid whole page crash. We will show these errors as a popup warnings to the user. It is needed to allow users without all privileges to search or users without privilege to see secrets to access pods page (see related issues below).
- `HandleError()` function was introduced. It distinguishes critical errors from non-critical ones. In the future `HandleErrors()` should be introduced too (it should work with multiple errors on input. Also methods to append errors to existing structures may be needed. It keeps code changes at the minimum.
- All non-critical errors are be logged. In the future popups on the frontend have to be added.
- **Refactored all resources list and detail pages to use new error handling.**

### Related issues

Closes #1976.

title: Fix cascade delete job and job associated pod
body:
Cascade delete job and job associated pod
Fix test

Replication Controller, Replica Set, StatefulSet, DaemonSet, and Deployment Cascading deletions are controlled by garbage-collection, but job resource is no Garbage Collection, job's pod is not ownerReferences.
https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/garbage-collection/
https://github.com/kubernetes/community/blob/548eb7292d45a4af78e0141d33094130dfe6080a/contributors/design-proposals/synchronous-garbage-collection.md

So I refer to the kuberctl delete job:
get job info->get job's pod->delete job's pod->delete job

title: Create an "Overview" page for namespaces
body: # Create an Overview page for namespaces Often when looking at the main dashboard page, users on my team want to see all of the objects associated with a particular namespace. **Currently it is only possible to see objects in the groups "Workloads", "Discovery and Load Balancing", and "Config and Storage".** This PR implements a button on the left sidebar that shows all the resources under those fields at the same time. This is my first pull request on the dashboard project and I am eager for suggestions and feedback! Please let me know if this diff is too big and I can submit the backend and frontend PRs separately. ## Backend A `/overview/` endpoint has been added to the api. The endpoint returns all of the objects included in "Workloads", "Discovery and Load Balancing", and "Config and Storage" for a given namespace. A new endpoint was created to be in keeping with the convention for "Workloads", "Discovery" etc. which all have their own endpoints. The `/search/` endpoint does something similar to `/overview/`, but it is not namespace specific. ## Frontend The frontend component is implemented using the `workloads` component as a guide. When allobjects is clicked, it hits the `/overview/` endpoint and pulls the desired resources.

title: Switch Go package manager to dep and update dependencies

`dep` is becoming most recommended tool and it is growing fast, so we should start using it since it is already better than other tools. Switching to it allowed to decrease `vendor` size from ~65 MB to ~36MB. Dependencies are easier to read and update.

``` sh
go get -u github.com/golang/dep/cmd/dep
dep init && dep ensure && dep prune
# remove untracked files
```

Closes #2197.
Closes #1890.

title: Add log in mechanism
body:
## Overview
Closes #2093.

This PR adds basic login functionality to dashboard. There are still many things to improve but after this initial version will be merged we will be able to split the work. It is based on [JSON Web Encryption](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7516) (JWE) standard.

### Data flow
Dashboard will generate encryption key during the start and it will be stored in a secret accessible by dashboard (not yet implemented).

1. User opens dashboard
1. Token is not present in a cookie and authorization header is not passed to dashboard
1. User fills in token field and clicks on login button
1. LoginSpec is sent to the backend (we'll make it work only over HTTPS)
1. Backend gets encryption key from a secret.
1. Token is taken and basic health check is made to see if it is recognized by apiserver.
1. Auth structure is encrypted and sent back to the frontend.
1. Frontend stores encrypted token in a cookie and user is redirected to the default state.
1. Cookie is passed to the backend on every request, decrypted there and auth info is used to create client.

This is the basic flow. In case authorization header is sent to the dashboard it will override our log in mechanism and will be used instead.

## Changes
 - Added angular cookies.
 - Added login page and made it independent of chrome state.
 - Added new transition/request hooks to redirect user to login page in case he is not logged in.
 - Added support for token based log in.
 - Adapted nav bar to be able to correctly show/hide it during initial page load. Before that nav component settings were overriding other components so I have moved logic to the nav service.
 - Added `go-jose` as a dependency for managing JWE tokens.

## Current limitations
 - Only token based login is supported
 - Encryption key is generated on backend. Backend crash means that stored token will be invalid
 - Because of previous issue dashboard can not be scaled

## Improvements
List of things to improve will be tracked from #2207.

## TODO
List of things to be done before the merge.

 - [x] Add JSDoc
 - [x] Add documentation
 - [x] Remove hardcoded strings (state, token name, etc.)
 - [x] Refactor the code
 - [x] Add tests
 - [x] Test on serve:prod
 
## UX
We'll rework it after everything is stable. For now it's very simple. There was also basic login option but I have disabled it for now due to https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/49709. 

![zrzut ekranu z 2017-07-28 12-56-16](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2285385/28714553-31028e16-7394-11e7-89f6-9c17cbec4905.png)

![zrzut ekranu z 2017-07-28 12-56-44](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2285385/28714566-3c86b474-7394-11e7-89c4-626dfe637397.png)

Calling @kubernetes/dashboard-maintainers and @liggitt

title: Add encryption key storing mechanism
body:
~I have to refactor the code and cleanup some things but it already shows the basic idea and works fine from what I've tested.~ It might need some improvements when key rotation mechanism will be added.

## Changes
 - Added secret synchronizer that is mainly responsible for watching on a single resource changes.
 - Added encryption key import/export option in order to be able to save it in a secret. Thanks to https://stackoverflow.com/a/44688503.
 - Adapted token manager to use key holder which uses secret synchronizer in order to import/export encryption key.
 - Added `Overwatch` that is started automatically with backend and is responsible for starting and watching over every registered synchronizer. Every synchronizer with restart policy `Always` will be restarted in case of error.

## TODO
 - [x] Refactor code
 - [x] Add documentation
 - [x] Add tests

Backend will always generate encryption key on start and try to push it to a secret. After it is created synchronizer basically watches for secret updates. On every update, handler registered by key holder is fired and encryption key is updated. As all backends will always be watching for the same resource, key from last event will be used.

In case of decryption error we can always force single update from secret and try once again.

Use the client-go deployment method instead of the kubectl deployment method, because the â€œk8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectlâ€ depend on too many kunernetes packages.
So that dashboard and kubernetes are tightly coupled .
In this way, dashboard  and kubernetes  can be loosely coupled, and the next step we can remove most of  the kubernetes packages.

title: Support for User Links add through annotations for Pods and Services
body:
I added support for user custom links that can be added as annotations to Pods and Services. 
For example: absolute vs relative links
alpha.dashboard.kubernetes.io/links: |
 {
     "debug":"{{apiserver-proxy-url}}/debug",   // relative path using the apiserver proxy urls
     "request":"http://www.someurl.com/debug/requests"   // absolute path since its includes http://
}

This pr is just covers two use cases and we plan on introducing more in subsequent pr's, especially after we get the global settings feature merged so that we can replace placeholder vars with global settings var values at run-time.

We also want to extend flexibility by constructing URLs at run-time based on:
- pod dns names
- labels?
- etc

title: Update dependencies
body:
Closes #2253 and closes #2244.

Updated manually `google-closure-compiler` and `webpack-stream` to latest versions.

## Important changes
 - Module resolution `LEGACY` has been removed from `google-closure-compiler`. I have changed it to `NODE` and fixed all errors and warnings.
 - Updated ECMAScript preset to `env` which contains all features from ES2015 together with new features from ES2016 and ES2017. We'll be slowly migrating to use new [async and await](http://babeljs.io/docs/plugins/transform-async-to-generator/) syntax and more. 
 - Updated closure compiler input language to `ECMASCRIPT_2017`.
 - Updated `webpack` configuration to match webpack 3.
 - Updated minor versions of other dependencies, i.e. angular to `1.6.6`
 - Reenabled compiler check `analyzerChecks`.

### **NOTE: All our imports have to start with `/`, `./` or `../` now, however I'd prefer to use options 2 and 3.**

I have left one new option disabled for now `new_type_inf` as it requires many more changes and is more strict when it comes to type checks.

title: Add token expiration/refresh feature
body:
Related to #2207.

### Changes
 - Added `--tokenTTL` argument to dashboard.
 - Default token expiration time has been set to 15 minutes
 - Token is refreshed with every state change in dashboard
 - In case token has expired user will be automatically redirected to login page with information that `Session expired. Please log in again.` Same behaviour is applied in case token can not be decrypted.

title: Fix tooltips across whole app
body:
We should use `md-delay="500"` and use `md-autohide` on all of our `md-tooltip` elements. Unfortunately, there is no clean way to do it, because:

-  `md-tooltip` element disappears from HTML just after compiling so custom attribute directive won't work
- wrapping `md-tooltip` in our component is also not an option because tooltip works only on the parent element and it this case it would be our new component (we cannot use replace when transcluding because it is deprecated)
- overriding `md-tooltip` to make it use our defaults is also not possible due to component original implementation
- copying `md-tooltip` to our code base is also not a good option

Therefore, I've changed fixed all occurences of `md-tooltip` in our codebase to:

``` html
<md-tooltip md-delay="500" md-autohide>
   ...
</md-tooltip>
```
### Checklist

- [x] fix all occurrences
- [x] update docs

### Related tasks

Closes #1734.
Closes #690.

title: Add periodic check for metric client health
body:
Resolves #2306 and resolves #2251.

Added new flag `metric-client-check-period` that defines how often health check against configured metric client will be run. By default it is set to 30 seconds.

title: Improve 404 error handling
body: Fixes #2149.

title: Include Init Containers in Logs
body: Fix for #2358. This change updates the `GetContainerNames` function to also include Init Containers; the impact of this being you can now view the Logs of Init Containers. (copy-migrations and run-migrations are both init-containers)

title: Fix minor issues and update deploy files
body:
## Changes
- Change text `log in` to `sign in`.
- Fix overwatch not restarting synchronizer in case of missing watch permissions for secret.
- Fix issue with accessing pod details page when user had no access to creator of the pod.
- Update and remove unused head yaml files to match 1.7 release requirements.

As for the last change, I believe that starting from 1.7 we should only support secure setup of Dashboard. This means that in case user has a cluster with authorization and authentication disabled he has to prepare yaml file on his own. 

Right now I have granted minimal privileges to dashboard required to start and run without issues.
- `create` and `watch` permission for secrets in `kube-system` namespace in order to create and watch for changes of `kubernetes-dashboard-key-holder` secret.
- `get`, `update` and `delete` permissions for secret named `kubernetes-dashboard-key-holder` in `kube-system` namespace.
- `proxy` permission to `heapster` service in `kube-system` namespace in order to allow getting metrics from heapster.

title: Fix logging in when using kubectl proxy
body:
Note in [Accessing Dashboard](https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/wiki/Accessing-Dashboard---1.7.X-and-above#kubectl-proxy) guide describes this change.

It makes sure that our token will not be saved unless Dashboard is accessed over HTTPS or locally (`127.0.0.1` or `localhost` domains) using `kubectl proxy`. Exposing Dashboard using `kubectl proxy --address ip ...` will not allow to log in.

title: Disable HTTP when serving HTTPS
body: This change will make sure that Dashboard is either served on HTTP or HTTPS only.

title: Revert "Prepare for 1.7.0 release"
body:
Reverts kubernetes/dashboard#2366

Was trying to create images, but there are some problems with the init container. At the moment it will only work for amd64 arch, since the base ubuntu image is a amd64 image. 

Also I think I'd prefer it if we can move it to gcr too for official release.

title: Prepare for 1.7.0 release
body:
Reopen of #2366.

We need to fix issues mentioned in #2389 before making the release.

title: Show previous container logs
body:
Fixes https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/1995 (logs part)

Currently, there is no way to see logs of a crashed container. In other words, after crash a new container instance will be created with a new log file, but for debugging the previous logs are more interessting.

Kubectl (and API) provide a previous flag to see the previous logs. Added button to logs view to see logs of previous container instance

title: clean up headers
body:
Did some manual testing and grep searches.

1. Removed 2 double licenses
2. Replaced a couple of old Google licenses with current template
3. Removed unused favicon originally generated by yeoman

I noticed we are using Kubernetes Dashboard Autors. Other projects use Kubernetes Autors e.g. kops, minikube. Not sure if it matters. I think we should merge to make it consistent and then make a quick replace with all headers to be on the save side. I can do so.

title: Make environment variables defined in envFrom shown in pod detail page
body:
Fix #2343 

This commit create EnvVars from every item in referenced ConfigMap or Secret, then add them to the container info. 

The following is an example.

![pod_detail](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/489448/30755211-6752236e-9f8b-11e7-8762-afdf7af36b52.png)

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: env-variables
spec:
  containers:
  - name: test
    image: gcr.io/google_containers/busybox
    command: [ "sh", "-c"]
    args:
    - while true; do
        echo -en '\n';
        printenv CONST_USER;
        printenv CONFIG_USER;
        printenv SECRET_USER;
        printenv TEST_FROM_CONFIG_USER;
        printenv TEST_FROM_CONFIG_TITLE;
        printenv FROM_SECRET_USER;
        printenv FROM_SECRET_TITLE;
        sleep 10;
      done;
    env:
    - name: CONST_USER
      value: alice
    - name: CONFIG_USER
      valueFrom:
        configMapKeyRef:
          name: config-env
          key: username
    - name: SECRET_USER
      valueFrom:
        secretKeyRef:
          name: secret-env
          key: username
    envFrom:
      - prefix: TEST_
        configMapRef:
          name: config-env-from
      - secretRef:
          name: secret-env-from
---
kind: ConfigMap
apiVersion: v1
metadata:
  name: config-env
data:
  username: bob
---
kind: Secret
apiVersion: v1
metadata:
  name: secret-env
data:
  username: Y2hhcmxpZQ==
---
kind: ConfigMap
apiVersion: v1
metadata:
  name: config-env-from
data:
  FROM_CONFIG_USER: david
  FROM_CONFIG_TITLE: programmer
---
kind: Secret
apiVersion: v1
metadata:
  name: secret-env-from
data:
  FROM_SECRET_USER: ZXZl
  FROM_SECRET_JOB: ZGVzaWduZXI=
```

title: Fix high cpu usage
body:
## Changes
- Fixes #2401 
- Remove `bower_components/` from `.gitignore`.
- Update `package-lock.json`

For anyone interested in actual cause and fix. Below you can find a description of the problem.

## Cause
Profiling `dashboard` binary showed function that caused high CPU usage.
```bash
(pprof) top
29440ms of 29990ms total (98.17%)
Showing top 10 nodes out of 12 (cum >= 560ms)
      flat  flat%   sum%        cum   cum%
    7620ms 25.41% 25.41%    29990ms   100%  github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/src/app/backend/sync.(*secretSynchronizer).Start.func1
(pprof) peek
29990ms of 29990ms total (  100%)
----------------------------------------------------------+-------------
      flat  flat%   sum%        cum   cum%   calls calls% + context 	 	 
----------------------------------------------------------+-------------
                                           29990ms   100% |   runtime.goexit
    7620ms 25.41% 25.41%    29990ms   100%                | github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/src/app/backend/sync.(*secretSynchronizer).Start.func1
                                           13840ms 61.87% |   runtime.chanrecv1
                                            7980ms 35.67% |   github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/src/app/backend/sync.(*secretSynchronizer).handleEvent
                                             550ms  2.46% |   github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/vendor/k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/watch.(*StreamWatcher).ResultChan
```

Compared to other functions, goroutine started in `secretSynchronizer.Start` method took most CPU time.
```golang
for {
	select {
	case ev, ok := <-watcher.ResultChan():
		if err := self.handleEvent(ev); err != nil {
			self.errChan <- err
			return
		}
	}
}
```

The problem was that after some time kubernetes watcher times out without any reason and `ResultChan` is closed. That caused infinite `for` loop. Given that it was running in another goroutine, dashboard was still responsive.

## Fix
Simple check if channel was closed did the trick.
```golang
case ev, ok := <-watcher.ResultChan():
	if !ok {
		self.errChan <- fmt.Errorf("%s watch ended with timeout", self.Name())
		return
	}
...
```

title: Fix Dashboard crash after exec into pod when using proxy
body:
Related to #2029 

Dashboard was crashing when trying to exec into pod. This was caused by missing `tmp` directory in the dashboard container. I have added `/tmp` mount that will be stored ~in memory~ on disk. 

Tested on k8s `1.7.7`. Exec works fine when accessing Dashboard using NodePort and kubectl proxy.

title: Add cert auto-generation and insecure login options
body:
This PR introduces 2 new flags to dashboard:
- `--auto-generate-certificates`
- `--enable-insecure-login`

### Auto-generate certificates
It allows us to get rid of init container. Passing `--auto-generate-certificates` option will make Dashboard generate self-signed certs and store them in directory specified by `--default-cert-dir` flag.

### Insecure login
As per request from some of our users I have also added option to enable login view when Dashboard is not served directly over HTTPS. It allows users to benefit from login functionality at their own risk.

### Build
Build pipeline has been adjusted and 2 new arguments can be passed when serving Dashboard in dev mode.
Use `gulp serve <arguments>`

New arguments:
- `--autoGenerateCerts`
- `--defaultCertDir=<path>`

#### TODO
- [x] Add tests
- [x] Add documentation

body:
Closes #2606 and closes #2566 as I have used SelfSubjectAccessReview API to determine if users can access given page.

## Changes
- Add `CanI` method to client manager so we can check if current user has access to given endpoint.
- Add `/cani` subresource url to `global/settings` endpoint. This way `cani` logic for every endpoint can be kept in backend instead of frontend.
- Refactor `client` package to follow other packages and extract types to `api/types.go` file.
- Add `AuthorizerService` in frontend with appropriate proxy method to get resurces from backend. In case user does not have access to given page `403 Forbidden Access` error will be shown. It can be extended later to support more verbs like PUT and DELETE.
- Fix race condition that caused SIGSEGV error during Dashboard start (related to secret synchronization).

## Todo
- [x] Add documentation
- [x] Add tests

body: Closes #2612

title: Remove asterisk from login view input fields
body:
Applied suggestion from https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/2641#issuecomment-349622463.

Closes #2641. For now, this is all we can do. We can revisit adding full support for password managers if their logic will be updated. Also we are still considering complete redesign of login view. In case it will happen we will keep in mind supporting password managers.

title: Update secret instead of deleting and recreating
body:
Closes #2629 

It is the only place we needed to update in order to be able to remove create secret permissions if kube addon manager is enabled and manages our key holder secret.

title: Auto-generate certs in-memory
body:
The dashboard is currently writing autogenerated cert files to a directory managed by the kubelet secret mounter.

At best, those files are auto-removed shortly after being written and the server startup races with the removal.

At worst, the location is mounted readonly and the dashboard fails to start.

There's no reason to write files to a location where they will just be cleaned up later (and doing so is breaking the dashboard when the location is read-only... see https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/58720/files#diff-7ab88bb7654d97946d6328f11f29d177)

This PR changes the dashboard to keep auto-generated certs in memory

title: hide nodePort in internal endpoints when nodePort is not set
body:
### What this PR does

When nodePort is not set for a service, hide the nodePort endpoint rather than display a <service>:0 endpoint.

### How to reproduce it

1. deploy a ClusterIP type service
```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-service1
  labels:
    app: nginx-svc
spec:
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    name: http
    port: 30080
    targetPort: 80
  type: ClusterIP
```

2. open Dashboard - Service list
3. check Internal endpoints column of the service above
```
my-service1:30080 TCP
my-service1:0 TCP
```

### How to fix it

Add a ng-if directive for Internal endpoints fields

title: Secret Volume Mode
body:
The pod will error when using the `--auto-generate-certificates` flag
while trying to write the cert file. This is because a secret's volume mode is set to `0400` by default.  See
[docs](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/secret/)

Release Notes 5.0.0
  • Remove d3-request; add d3-fetch.
  • Remove d3-queue; see Promise.all.
  • Add d3-scale-chromatic.
  • Add d3-contour.
  • Add selection.clone.
  • Add d3.create.
  • Add projection.angle.
  • Remove d3.schemeCategory20* categorical color schemes. (See note below.)
  • Fix duplicate installation of D3 modules at different versions. (#3256)
  • Fix d3.formatâ€™s SI format for locales with currency suffixes.

D3 now includes new categorical color schemes from ColorBrewer, along with ColorBrewerâ€™s excellent diverging, sequential single-hue and sequential multi-hue color schemes. The twenty-color schemes were removed because their grouped design often falsely implied non-existent relationships in the data: a shared hue can imply that the encoded data are part of a group (a super-category), while the relative lightness can falsely imply order.

title: fix: namespace param should be checked in onEnter hook
body:
Related issue:
https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/issues/2974


The issue is related to how app is initialized:

1. user hits `k8s-ui.com`
2. app load default state, with namespace = `''`
3. `kubernetesDashboard.common.namespace` module 's `run` method checks `ensureNamespaceParamPresent`. Since no namespace presents in the url, the app then reload with namespace = `'default'`

By changing the hook from onSuccess to onEnter, overview state (and any other state) will always success with a non empty namespace.

title: chore: add kubernetes-sigs/application dep
body:
Preparation for adding application list to dashboard.

What I did:

- Align `gopkg.toml` with `github.com/kubernetes-sigs/application`
- Run `dep ensure -v -add github.com/kubernetes-sigs/application/pkg`
- Add local go files which depends on client&types in `github.com/kubernetes-sigs/application` package
- Run `dep prune` to remove unused dependencies
- Run `gulp check-ci` to make sure build/e2e still works

title: Include gulp and updated npm in build/Dockerfile for easier development
body:
Hi all!

I wanted to start contributing more to this repo but found that spinning up a development environment wasn't that easy (for reference I'm on OSX and had a couple others follow the docs and run into trouble)

What this does is simple: update NPM and install Gulp. This should not affect anything else the container is used for. What this does is allow people to more easily spin up and use the container to run as their dev environment without invoking Gulp (instead Gulp is used within the container)

From there, spinning up a dev environment is as easy as:

```
docker build -t kubernetes-dashboard-build-image build/
docker run --rm -e KUBE_DASHBOARD_APISERVER_HOST=http://192.168.2.1:8080 -p 3001:3001 -p 9090:9090 -p 9091:9091 -ti -v $(pwd):/app kubernetes-dashboard-build-image gulp serve
kubectl proxy --port=8080 --accept-hosts='^.*$'
```

Once this (hopefully) gets merged, I'd like to update the Getting Started documentation to reflect this as a more streamlined way to spin up a development environment. :)

Thanks!

<summary>âœ¨ How do dependency updates work with Greenkeeper?</summary>

After you merge this pull request, **Greenkeeper will create a new branch whenever a  dependency is updated**, with the new version applied. The branch creation should trigger your testing services and check whether your code still works with the new dependency version. Depending on the the results of these tests Greenkeeper will try to open meaningful and helpful pull requests and issues, so your dependencies remain working and up-to-date.

```diff
-  "underscore": "^1.6.0"
+  "underscore": "^1.7.0"
```

The above example shows an in-range update. `1.7.0` is included in the old `^1.6.0` range, because of the [caret `^` character ](https://docs.npmjs.com/misc/semver#ranges).
When the test services report success Greenkeeper will silently delete the branch again, because no action needs to be taken â€“ everything is fine.

However, should the tests fail, Greenkeeper will create an issue to inform you about the problem immediately.

This way, youâ€™ll never be surprised by a dependency breaking your code. As long as everything still works, Greenkeeper will stay out of your way, and as soon as something goes wrong, youâ€™ll be the first to know.

```diff

+  "lodash": "^4.0.0"
```

In this example, the new version `4.0.0` is _not_ included in the old `^3.0.0` range.
For version updates like these â€“ letâ€™s call them â€œout of rangeâ€ updates â€“ youâ€™ll receive a pull request.

This means that **you no longer need to check for new versions manually** â€“ Greenkeeper will keep you up to date automatically.

These pull requests not only serve as reminders to update: If you have solid tests and good coverage, and the pull requests passes those tests, you can very likely just merge it and release a new version of your software straight away :shipit:

title: fix: fix circular dependencies issues and enable serve without AoT
body:
Before the PR, the app is served with `--aot` option and the local dev recompilation is time consuming and annoying. After I turned off --aot, I found that the app has some circular dependency issues.

The issue is mainly caused by that the global service module and dialog module has some indirect imports between each other. A safer way is to move the dialog module to the parent of global service module, thus global service module and dialog module would have the same level of import paths.

Also resource service module is not necessarily imported by many features since it is a provider only module.

After the PR, we can develop the Angular branch without `--aot` option, and the recompilation should be significantly improved.

title: API request logging improvements
body:
Hey all!

This directly addresses #3174, #3012, and potentially others. 

I created a list of addresses that may potentially have sensitive information that should not be logged. Instead it will only log `{ contents hidden }`. 

However, in some cases (like debugging and development) you still want to see what's being passed along. So I added a new CLI argument to the dashboard called `--api-log-level` with three options: INFO,DEBUG,NONE

The default setting is INFO, which will log everything but sensitive URLs. 
NONE will turn off all request/response logging.
DEBUG will log everything including the contents of sensitive URLs.

I added tests for all this, and also updated `TestFormatRequestLog` to handle more diverse test cases.

Thanks!

title: Add namespace support
body:
When deploying the K8s Dashboard, it's possible to scope it to a certain namespace. Yet even within a namespace, other than `kube-system`, the dashboard will still try to add secrets to the `kube-system` ns.

This attempts to open the discussion around how to fix it. In this case, I've added a simple flag to the binary (still needs some tests and url validation).

The following flag was added:
`--namespace string   When non-default namespace is used, create encryption key in the specified namespace. Default: 'kube-system'. (default "kube-system")`

Another idea is for the dashboard to lookup what namespace it's running in, and simply use that. :fire: and :speaking_head:  are welcome :)

/assign @ianlewis

title: Add container for development outside cluster
body:
To construct thinner development environment outside cluster
with docker, this adds Dockerfile and shell scripts.

This container will run npm command as you like, or install and run 
dashboard. 

Also, this adds chrome driver as headless for testing in container.

The following commands are reviewed in this:
* npm ci
* npm run check
* npm run test:frontend
* npm run test:backend
* npm run start

To run this container:
1. Copy kubeconfig from your cluster, and confirm URL for API server in it.
2. Set filepath for kubeconfig into K8S_DASHBOARD_KUBECONFIG environment variable.
3. Change directory into your dashboard source directory.
4. To install and run dashboard, simply run `aio/develop/run-npm-on-container.sh`.

If you want to run npm command in this container as you like, run like follows:
`aio/develop/run-npm-on-container.sh run check`
`aio/develop/run-npm-on-container.sh run test:backend`

ðŸ”’ Greenkeeper has found a `package-lock.json` file in this repository. Greenkeeper supports lockfile updates for public packages. If you use private packages in your repository, please use [greenkeeper-lockfile](https://github.com/greenkeeperio/greenkeeper-lockfile) to make sure these can get updated as well.

This pull request **updates all your dependencies to their latest version**. Having them all up to date really is the best starting point for keeping up with new releases. To solve the issue, first find out which of the dependencyâ€™s updates is causing the problem. Then fix your code to accomodate the changes in the updated dependency. [next-update](https://www.npmjs.com/package/next-update) is a really handy tool to help you with this.

Then push your changes to this branch and merge it.
</details>
<details>
<summary>ðŸ— How to configure Travis CI</summary>

Greenkeeper has added a rule to your `.travis.yml` that whitelists Greenkeeper branches, which are created when your dependencies are updated. Travis CI will run your tests on these branches automatically to see if they still pass.

No additional setup is required ðŸ˜Š

You may have good reasons for not wanting to update to a certain dependency right now. In this case, you can [change the dependencyâ€™s version string in the `package.json` file back to whatever you prefer](https://github.com/kubernetes/dashboard/edit/greenkeeper/initial/package.json).

To make sure Greenkeeper doesnâ€™t nag you again on the next update, add a `greenkeeper.ignore` field to your `package.json`, containing a list of dependencies you donâ€™t want to update.

```js
// package.json
{
  â€¦
  "greenkeeper": {
    "ignore": [
      "package-names",
      "you-want-me-to-ignore"
    ]
  }
}
```
</details>

<summary>ðŸ‘©â€ðŸ’» How to update this pull request</summary>

```bash
  # Change into your repositoryâ€™s directory

  npm install-test
  # Adapt your code until everything works again

```
</details>
<details>
<summary>âœ¨ How do dependency updates work with Greenkeeper?</summary>

After you merge this pull request, **Greenkeeper will create a new branch whenever a  dependency is updated**, with the new version applied. The branch creation should trigger your testing services and check whether your code still works with the new dependency version. Depending on the the results of these tests Greenkeeper will try to open meaningful and helpful pull requests and issues, so your dependencies remain working and up-to-date.

```diff
-  "underscore": "^1.6.0"
+  "underscore": "^1.7.0"
```

The above example shows an in-range update. `1.7.0` is included in the old `^1.6.0` range, because of the [caret `^` character ](https://docs.npmjs.com/misc/semver#ranges).
When the test services report success Greenkeeper will silently delete the branch again, because no action needs to be taken â€“ everything is fine.

However, should the tests fail, Greenkeeper will create an issue to inform you about the problem immediately.

This way, youâ€™ll never be surprised by a dependency breaking your code. As long as everything still works, Greenkeeper will stay out of your way, and as soon as something goes wrong, youâ€™ll be the first to know.

```diff
-  "lodash": "^3.0.0"
+  "lodash": "^4.0.0"
```

In this example, the new version `4.0.0` is _not_ included in the old `^3.0.0` range.
For version updates like these â€“ letâ€™s call them â€œout of rangeâ€ updates â€“ youâ€™ll receive a pull request.

This means that **you no longer need to check for new versions manually** â€“ Greenkeeper will keep you up to date automatically.

These pull requests not only serve as reminders to update: If you have solid tests and good coverage, and the pull requests passes those tests, you can very likely just merge it and release a new version of your software straight away :shipit:

title: Add Metrics Scaper object definitions
body: This is an interim PR to add the object definitions required for the Dashboard Scraper integration. This needs to be merged in before the rest of the WIP PR so work can proceed finishing the Scraper container (as the Scraper calls on and requires these definition)

title: Change e2e tests to use kind
body:
Fixes #3539 

Several things are moving to use [Kind](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kind) in place of Minikube. This is luckily a pretty easy swap for us as our e2e test is the only thing reliant on Minikube. 

Performance comparisons:
Minikube: https://travis-ci.org/kubernetes/dashboard/builds/484938232
Kind: https://travis-ci.com/jeefy/dashboard/builds/98754147

While this might seem unnecessary now, it will definitely benefit us later.

Comment, discuss, and iterate. :)

title: Support $KUBECONFIG
body:
As we start using Kind more, we're reliant on the way they manage their kubecfg files: Through setting $KUBECONFIG`. Locally I keep having to change `package.json` or `.npmrc` to use it. We can do better.

This wraps `gulp serve` in a script that checks to see if `$KUBECONFIG` is set. If it is, it uses it. Otherwise, it defaults to the `kubernetes-dashboard:kubeconfig` values in `.npmrc`

I would have avoided _yet another wrapper script_ but I can't put the necessary logic in `.npmrc`, and it'd be super ugly in `package.json`

Feedback, if any, is appreciated. :)

title: [WIP] Introduce angular router and add error handling
body:
This PR is far from finished yet :slightly_smiling_face: 

Current changes:
- Refactor error handling on the backend to a single package. All errors should be created using our internal package.
- Start replacement process of `ui-router` to `angular-router`. 

What's missing:
- [x] Proper query params handling. By default, it should at least have `namespace` query set to `default` namespace.
- [x] Proper path params handling for detail views. Only `Cluster Role` details view is working right now.
- [ ] Remove usage of old `ui-router` classes i.e. `StateService`, `Transition`, etc. in all places and replace them with angular router equivalents.
- [ ] Breadcrumbs.
- [ ] Actionbars.
- [ ] Exec, logs, search etc.

title: Simplify backend code
body:
- Drops unused fields from detail structs (closes #3595).
- Uses struct inheritance to simplify detail structs (closes #2453).
- Aligns classes in `backendapi.d.ts` with the backend.
- Switch to apps/v1.

title: Improve container for development
body:
Setting up environment inside container and enabling to run more npm commands for dashboard.

Also, changed default command for the container from only `npm start` to `npm run cluster:start` before start. It means this script creates k8s cluster in another container using `kind`, so we don't need to install k8s cluster independently before running dashboard.

Enabled npm commands are follows:
* build
* test:e2e
* cluster:start
* cluster:stop

title: Bump `kind` version to 0.2.1
body: Quick version bump. :)

title: Use settingsApi.SettingsManager in CreateHTTPAPIHandler
body:
Currently the CreateHTTPAPIHandler requires a settings.SettingsManager instead of an api.SettingsManager, which means you can't provide a different implementation if you want to embed the Handler with a different SettingsManager. The SettingsManager interface wasn't actually used anywhere and was out of sync with the implementation, so I've updated the interface to match.

The SettingsManager took in a clientManager, which was only used by the SettingsHandler. This PR moves the clientManager to the SettingsHandler.
